Comparing Event Prediction Packages

The purpose of this document is to compare three Event Prediction Packages:

  • gestate,

  • eventTrack, and

  • eventPrediction.

In this document I will provide answers to the following questions by working through several vignettes provided by the packages:

  1. What distributions are used to model time-to-event outcomes?

  2. Does the software model censoring?

  3. How should the data be organized as an input to the main function for each package?

  4. Which package was easiest to understand?

I am going to work through the vignettes and provide some details on the different decisions you have to make and the key functions that are being used.

gestate example/vignette

The gestate package gives tools to help with planning and monitoring time-to-event trials, specifically when complicated censoring and non-proportional hazards come up. There are three main components of the package:

  • The first is analytic calculation of predicted time-to-event trial properties, providing estimates of expected hazard ratio, event numbers and power under different analysis methods.

  • The second is simulation, allowing stochastic estimation of these same properties.

  • Thirdly, it provides parametric event prediction using blinded trial data, including creation of prediction intervals. Methods are based upon numerical integration and a flexible object-orientated structure for defining event, censoring and recruitment distributions (Curves).

Installing the package is straightforward and is available on the CRAN.

1. What distributions are used to model time-to-event outcomes

Available Event and Censoring Distributions

In gestate curves are created to represent the event and/or sensoring distributions. The above image illustrates the different types of distributions (and the associated functions) available in this package.

To create these curves, you use the various associated functions.

Now that we have the distributions, we can start to look at the key functions available through this package.

The main function we will start with is the nph_traj function, which calculates time-to-event trial properties for complex assumptions. The functions does power calculations, so it can be performed for sample size planning.

At a minimum, nph_traj requires a Curve object to describe the distribution of each of the active and control arms (‘active_ecurve’ and ‘control_ecurve’ arguments respectively), as well as an RCurve object (‘rcurve’ argument) to describe the recruitment distribution. The distributions of the active and control arms should typically be estimated based upon parameters or curve-fitting from previous trials (using e.g. fit_KM or fit_tte_data from the gestate package).

2. Does the software model censoring?

Administrative censoring is handled implicitly based upon the specified RCurve object. However, dropout censoring is also common in time-to-event trials. This can be specified through Curve objects, and separate censoring distributions are supported for each arm. By default, gestate uses no censoring via the Blank() Curve.

It should be noted that the required censoring distributions must represent that of the censoring that would occur in the absence of events or administrative censoring. The observed numbers of censored patients in each arm will therefore also depend partially on the event distributions. The suggested way to use existing data to parameterise the censoring distributions is to create ‘reverse Kaplan Meier’ plots of existing data, whereby dropout censorings are ‘events’, and both events and administrative censorings are ‘censorings’.

# Creating Active and Control censoring curves
censorCurveA <- Exponential(lambda=0.001)
censorCurveC <- Exponential(lambda=0.002)

output1 <- nph_traj(active_ecurve=activeCurve,
               control_ecurve=controlCurve,
               active_dcurve=censorCurveA,
               control_dcurve=censorCurveC,
               rcurve=curveRecPieceRMaxF,
               max_assessment=10,
               HRbound=1.3, # HR Value to test landmark significance against
               detailed_output = TRUE,
               required_power = 0.9)

3. How should the data be organized as an input to the main function for each package?

example_distribution <- Weibull(alpha=100,beta=0.8)
example_recruitment  <- LinearR(rlength=24,Nactive=600,Ncontrol=0)

# Create the full trajectory
maxtime <- 100
example_data_long <- 
  simulate_trials(active_ecurve = example_distribution,
                  control_ecurve = example_distribution,
                  rcurve = example_recruitment,
                  assess=maxtime,
                  iterations=1,
                  seed=1234567,
                  detailed_output=TRUE)

# Shrink the trajectory to an early time point at which event prediction will occur
example_data_short <- set_assess_time(example_data_long,18)

# Create an RCurve incorporating both observed and predicted recruitment with arbitrary randomisation ratio of 1
recruit <- PieceR(matrix(c(rep(1,12),10,15,25,30,45,60,55,50,65,60,55,30),ncol=2),1)

trial_long <- simulate_trials(active_ecurve=Weibull(50,0.8),control_ecurve=Weibull(50,0.8),rcurve=recruit,fix_events=200,iterations=1,seed=12345,detailed_output=TRUE)
# Create a shortened version with data for use in the event prediction
trial_short <- set_assess_time(data=trial_long,time=10,detailed_output = FALSE)
# Create the trajectory of events
maxtime <- max(ceiling(trial_long[,"Assess"]))
events <- rep(NA,maxtime)
for (i in 1:maxtime){
  events[i] <- sum(1-set_assess_time(trial_long,i)[,"Censored"])
}
predictions <- event_prediction(data=trial_short, Event="Censored", censoringOne=TRUE, type="Weibull", rcurve=recruit,max_time=60, cond_Events=49, cond_NatRisk=451, cond_Time=10, units="Months")

# Plot observed events and conditional predictions
plot_ep(predictions,trajectory="conditional",which_PI="conditional",max_time=40,observed=events,target=200,max_E=200)

trial_less_short <- set_assess_time(data=trial_long,time=14,detailed_output = FALSE)
predictions2 <- event_prediction(data=trial_less_short, Event="Censored",censoringOne=TRUE, type="Weibull", rcurve=recruit,max_time=60, cond_Events=101,cond_NatRisk=399,cond_Time=14, units="Months")

trial_mature <- set_assess_time(data=trial_long,time=18,detailed_output = FALSE)
predictions3 <- event_prediction(data=trial_mature, Event="Censored",censoringOne=TRUE, type="Weibull", rcurve=recruit,max_time=60, cond_Events=148,cond_NatRisk=352,cond_Time=18, units="Months")

eventTrack example/vignette

The eventTrack uses a Hybrid framework with a KM-curve and an exponential tail. It tends to utilize this hybrid framework in conjunction with the rpact package

In order to estimate the survival function the event prediction is based on, a piecewise exponential hazard function is fit to the time-to-event data to infer the potential change points. Prior to the last identified change point, the survival function is estimated using Kaplan-Meier, and the tail after the change point is fit using piecewise exponential.

#install.packages("eventTrack")
library(eventTrack)
 ls(asNamespace("eventTrack"))

## [11] "predictEventsUncond"
#install.packages(c("rpact", "fitdistrplus"))
library(rpact)          # to simulate illustrative dataset
library(fitdistrplus)   # to estimate Weibull fit

The next portion outlines how you predict an interim (IA) or final analysis (FA) clinical cutoff date (CCOD) in an ongoing trial, i.e. in a trial where

  • patients have already been recruited but have not yet experienced the event and/or

  • patients have already been recruited and have already experienced the event and/or

  • further patients will be recruited in the future.

2. Does the software model censoring?

Yes

3. How should the data be organized as an input to the main function for each package?

In order to make event predictions, a sufficiently clean dataset including accrual times and the relevant time-to-event endpoint data up to the CCOD is needed. In addition, if recruitment is not yet completed, a prediction regarding the accrual of the remaining patient is required as well.

The getDesignGroupSequential function from the rpact package sets up the boundaries and defines a group sequential design.

# ------------------------------------------------------------
# trial details 
# ------------------------------------------------------------

alpha <- 0.05 #Significance Level for Design
beta <- 0.2   #Type II Error Rate 

design <- getDesignGroupSequential(
  informationRates = 1, 
  typeOfDesign = "asOF", 
  sided = 1, 
  alpha = alpha, 
  beta = beta)
# max number of patients
maxNumberOfSubjects1 <- 500
maxNumberOfSubjects2 <- 500
maxNumberOfSubjects <- maxNumberOfSubjects1 + maxNumberOfSubjects2

# survival hazard
piecewiseSurvivalTime <- c(0, 6, 9)
lambda2 <- c(0.025, 0.04, 0.02)

# effect size
hr <- 0.75

# quantities that determine timing of reporting events
dout1 <- 0
dout2 <- 0
douttime <- 12
accrualTime <- 0
accrualIntensity <- 42

# maximal sample size
samplesize <- getSampleSizeSurvival(
                design = design, 
                piecewiseSurvivalTime = piecewiseSurvivalTime, 
                lambda2 = lambda2, 
                hazardRatio = hr, 
                dropoutRate1 = dout1, 
                dropoutRate2 = dout2, 
                dropoutTime = douttime, 
                accrualTime = accrualTime, 
                accrualIntensity = accrualIntensity,
                maxNumberOfSubjects = maxNumberOfSubjects)  

nevents <- as.vector(ceiling(samplesize$eventsPerStage))
# expected number of events overall and per group at 1-60 months after trial start
time <- 0:60 
probEvent <- getEventProbabilities(time = time, 
    piecewiseSurvivalTime = piecewiseSurvivalTime, 
    lambda2 = lambda2, 
    hazardRatio = hr,
    dropoutRate1 = dout1, 
    dropoutRate2 = dout2, 
    dropoutTime = douttime,
    accrualTime = accrualTime, 
    accrualIntensity = accrualIntensity, 
    maxNumberOfSubjects = maxNumberOfSubjects)

# extract expected number of events
expEvent <- probEvent$overallEventProbabilities * maxNumberOfSubjects   # overall
expEventInterv <- probEvent$eventProbabilities1 * maxNumberOfSubjects1  # intervention
expEventCtrl <- probEvent$eventProbabilities2 * maxNumberOfSubjects2   # control

# cumulative number of recruited patients over time
nSubjects <- getNumberOfSubjects(time = time, 
                                 accrualTime = accrualTime, 
                                 accrualIntensity = accrualIntensity, 
                                 maxNumberOfSubjects = maxNumberOfSubjects)

# plot results
plot(time, 
     nSubjects$numberOfSubjects, 
     type = "l", 
     lwd = 2,
     main = "Number of patients and expected number of events over time",
     xlab = "Time from trial start (months)",
     ylab = "Number of patients / events")
lines(time, expEvent, col = "blue", lwd = 2)
lines(time, expEventCtrl, col = "green")
lines(time, expEventInterv, col = "orange")
legend(x = 23, y = 850,
     legend = c("Recruitment", "Expected events - All subjects",
                "Expected events - Control", "Expected events - Intervention"),
       col = c("black", "blue", "green", "orange"), lty = 1, lwd = c(2, 2, 1, 1),
       bty = "n")

# add lines with event prediction pre-trial
fa_pred_pretrial <- exactDatesFromMonths(data.frame(1:length(expEvent) - 1, expEvent), nevents)
segments(fa_pred_pretrial, 0, fa_pred_pretrial, nevents, lwd = 2, lty = 2, col = "blue")
segments(0, nevents, fa_pred_pretrial, nevents, lwd = 2, lty = 2, col = "blue")

eventPrediction example/vignette

The eventPrediction package is a package that was developed by scientific computing solutions and can be found on their github site. It is a package that has not had recent updates, but can be downloaded from GitHub and unzipped into your local directory.

The eventPrediction package uses methods to predict either the required number to achieve a target or the expected time at which you will reach the required number of events. You can use this package in the design phase of clinical trials or in the reporting phase. Which means you can use it to simulate a trial based on a set of assumptions and run predictions and calculate uncertainties when your trial will finish. Alternatively you can upload your trial data, simulate additional patient recruitment based on observed one and run prediction on when the target number of event will be reached or the expected number of events at a given time.

Installation of this package and it’s vignettes was not fully straightforward, but it can be done with a little extra work.

#install.packages("~/R/win-library/4.1/eventPrediction-master.zip", repos = NULL, type = "win.binary")
library(eventPrediction)

# load()

1. What distributions are used to model time-to-event outcomes

To estimate time-to-event outcomes, the eventPrediction package uses Weibull and loglogistic models within the fit function from the survreg package.

2. Does the software model censoring?

Yes. We can use CensorInformation function to check out what has been censored.

3. How should the data be organized as an input to the main function for each package?

The data for input should be organized quite how you would normally organize data for survival analysis. An example can be seen below:

One issue that may arise, comes with dates. The following three date formats are recognized by the package: YYYY-MM-DD, DD/MM/YYYY and DD Month YYYY. You may have to do some date manipulation if your dates are not in the correct format.

To get started, we have to create an event data object. To do this, you utilize the EventData function, which is a constructor for an event data object.

#?EventData
my.data <- EventData(data=event.data, 
                     subject="subject",
                     rand.date="randDate",
                     has.event="hasEvent",
                     withdrawn="withdrawn",
                     time="time",
                     site="site", #optional
                     event.type="eventType") #optional

EventData function arguments:

  • data = Dataset with parameters

  • subject = Subject ID

  • rand.date = Data of randomization onto trial

  • has.event = Had an event or not

  • withdrawn = Withdrawn or not

  • time = days on trial until event

  • site = Center/hospital/location, etc

  • event.type = Type of Event that occurred

Fitting a model and Event Prediction

The simulate procedure is used to generate when events are expected to occur. This function uses the parameters of a fitted Weibull model (or loglogistic) to simulate the time-to-event for all subjects who have not had an event. Conditional Weibull distributions (or loglogistic) are used to take into account the time since randomization for each subject.

Use event data object within the fit function, which fits a survival model. Within this

my.fit <- fit(my.data)
my.fit
## Call:

We then can take the model and run simulations on the data. This is a simple version of the simulation, but you can add things like number of additional individuals accrued and who have dropped out.

results <- simulate(my.fit,
Nsim=500, #Number of simulations to perform
seed = 20141015) #A random seed for reproducibility

summary(results)
## 979 patients recruited where last patient in on 2015-11-26
## and last event observed at 2015-11-27 (699 events). Using
## weibull survival model.
plot(results)

Predictions

You can then feed in the results of the simulation into the predict function. Here, we can choose the predicted time for a number of events given by the event.pred argument. The event.pred argument can take a vector of values to check multiple predictions.

#?predict
results <- predict(results,
                   event.pred=c(700, 800, 900 ))
summary(results)

Comparisons Between the 3 Packages

1. What distributions are used to model time-to-event outcomes (for example, gestate uses the exponential, Weibull, and Log-Normal; I believe eventTrack used the KM curve with exponential tail)

gestate - Exponential, Weibull, Log-normal, generalized gamma eventTrack - KM curve and then an exponential/Weibull tail (Weibull fit requires the installation of another package) eventPrediction - Exponential, Weibull, loglogistic

2. Does the software model censoring?

Yes for all three

3. Shape of the data.

See vignettes.

4. Which package was easiest to understand?

gestate has a very nice vignette and documentation. It was easy to install and get started with. It is also available on the CRAN, which makes it easy to download. It appears to be the most fully featured and the most up to date of the three packages.

The eventTrack package was easy to install and did not have a lot of extra functions. It was built to be used on top of other mature packages, which makes it a bit more stable. I did find it to be the most unwieldy and it required a lot of inputs for the various functions. EventTrack does not appear to handle drop outs, like gestate.

Tricky to install and get eventPrediction started, since it is not updated to more recent standards and is only available through GitHub. However, it is pretty straightforward once you get everything installed.
